If formula_2 is a Lie group and formula_3 is a normal and closed (in the topological rather than the algebraic sense of the word) Lie subgroup of , the quotient formula_20 is also a Lie group. In this case, the original group "formula_2" has the structure of a fiber bundle (specifically, a principal -bundle), with base space formula_20 and fiber . The dimension of formula_20 equals .

Note that the condition that formula_3 is closed is necessary. Indeed, if formula_3 is not closed then the quotient space is not a T1-space (since there is a coset in the quotient which cannot be separated from the identity by an open set), and thus not a Hausdorff space.

For a non-normal Lie subgroup , the space formula_20 of left cosets is not a group, but simply a differentiable manifold on which formula_2 acts. The result is known as a homogeneous space.



Fundamental theorem on homomorphisms

In abstract algebra, the fundamental theorem on homomorphisms, also known as the fundamental homomorphism theorem, or the first isomorphism theorem, relates the structure of two objects between which a homomorphism is given, and of the kernel and image of the homomorphism.

The homomorphism theorem is used to prove the isomorphism theorems.

Given two groups "G" and "H" and a group homomorphism , let "N" be a normal subgroup in "G" and φ the natural surjective homomorphism (where "G"/"N" is the quotient group of "G" by "N"). If "N" is a subset of ker("f") then there exists a unique homomorphism such that .

In other words, the natural projection φ is universal among homomorphisms on "G" that map "N" to the identity element.

